## Executive Summary

The Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Japan is a major humanitarian donor,
with total funding peaking near \$296 million in 2025, reflecting
significant variability in year-to-year and regional allocations. Japan
demonstrates a strategic expansion of its aid footprint, increasing
recipient countries from 8 in 2022 to 35 in 2025, with notable
prioritization of global initiatives alongside targeted regional
funding. While Japan’s funding is moderately earmarked (about 23%), it
displays less flexibility compared to other donors, with fluctuating
transaction volumes and values that pose challenges for program
predictability. Aligning proposals with Japan’s evolving geographic and
thematic priorities, emphasizing global impact and emerging focus areas,
can enhance funding success.

This chart displays the funding volatility of the Ministry of Foreign
